  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "AB",
    "text": "That picture was most likely taken in Warsaw. It was originally a passport photographs, which I had enlarged. And I've lost the original photograph. This photograph is of my aunt and uncle from my mother's side. My aunt is the sister of my mother, maiden name Gold, her married name Benderman, with her husband Benderman. In between them is their son, who survived the war in Australia and lives in Israel presently. Both of my aunt and my uncle were murdered during the Warsaw Ghetto uprising. This photograph is of my sister, Mina Borensztejn. This picture was taken before the war, probably 1937 or '38. Her age was either 17 or 18. She was murdered in Warsaw Ghetto. This is a photograph of me, Adam Borensztejn, about six months after being liberated by the American army. I'm wearing a prison uniform striped jacket. My hair is just starting to grow. And I have gained in that picture, I would say, at least 50 or more pounds since liberation.",
